<li id="cite_note-18"><b><a href="#cite_ref-18" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFNorwich1967">Norwich, John J. (1967). <i>The Normans in the South 1016-1130</i>. pp.&#160;p.102.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Normans+in+the+South+1016-1130&amp;rft.aulast=Norwich&amp;rft.aufirst=John+J.&amp;rft.au=Norwich%2C+John+J.&amp;rft.date=1967&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3Bp.102&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:East-West_Schism"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-NorwichApogee-19">^ <a href="#cite_ref-NorwichApogee_19-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-NorwichApogee_19-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-NorwichApogee_19-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFNorwich1992">Norwich, John J. (1992). <i>Byzantium, The Apogee</i>. pp.&#160;pp.320-321.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Byzantium%2C+The+Apogee&amp;rft.aulast=Norwich&amp;rft.aufirst=John+J.&amp;rft.au=Norwich%2C+John+J.&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3Bpp.320-321&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:East-West_Schism"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-20"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book"><i><a href="http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13535a.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13535a.htm" rel="nofollow">New Catholic Encyclopedia</a></i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13535a.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13535a.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13535a.htm</a></span>.  ""...in 1053 he [Michael Caerularius] sends off a declaration of war, then shuts up the Latin churches at Constantinople, hurls a string of wild accusations, and shows in every possible way that he wants a schism, apparently for the mere pleasure of not being in communion with the West. He got his wish. After a series of wanton aggressions, unparalleled in church history, after he had begun by striking the pope's name from his diptychs, the Roman legates excommunicated him (16 July, 1054). But still there was no idea of a general excommunication of the Byzantine Church, still less of all the East. The legates carefully provided against that in their Bull. They acknowledged that the emperor (Constantine IX, who was excessively annoyed at the whole quarrel), the Senate, and the majority of the inhabitants of the city were "most pious and orthodox". They excommunicated Caerularius, Leo of Achrida, and their adherents. This quarrel, too, need no more have produced a permanent state of schism than the excommunication of any other contumacious bishop. The real tragedy is that gradually all the other Eastern patriarchs took sides with Caerularius, obeyed him by striking the pope's name from their diptychs, and chose of their own accord to share his schism. At first they do not seem to have wanted to do so. John III of Antioch certainly refused to go into schism at Caerularius's bidding. But, eventually, the habit they had acquired of looking to Constantinople for orders proved too strong. The emperor (not Constantine IX, but his successor) was on the side of his patriarch and they had learned too well to consider the emperor as their over-lord in spiritual matters too. Again, it was the usurped authority of Constantinople, the Erastianism of the East that turned a personal quarrel into a great schism.""</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=New+Catholic+Encyclopedia&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.newadvent.org%2Fcathen%2F13535a.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:East-West_Schism"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-21"><b><a href="#cite_ref-21" title="">^</a></b> Bishop Kallistos (Ware), p. 67</li>
<li id="cite_note-22"><b><a href="#cite_ref-22" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFGallagher2008">Gallagher, Clarence (2008). <i><a href="http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Pnkxofhi4mQC&amp;pg=PA596&amp;lpg=PA596&amp;dq=Massacre+of+the+Latins&amp;source=web&amp;ots=KZ5JtcG2jN&amp;sig=SJx8NwIiehNFz7OCT2ZIMSby1f8&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=RzGeSby8ONSujAetx6nLCw&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;resnum=10&amp;ct=result" class="external text" title="http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Pnkxofhi4mQC&amp;pg=PA596&amp;lpg=PA596&amp;dq=Massacre+of+the+Latins&amp;source=web&amp;ots=KZ5JtcG2jN&amp;sig=SJx8NwIiehNFz7OCT2ZIMSby1f8&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=RzGeSby8ONSujAetx6nLCw&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;resnum=10&amp;ct=result" rel="nofollow">The Oxford Handbook of Byzantine Studies</a></i>. Oxford University Press. pp.&#160;p.596. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0199252467" class="internal">ISBN 0199252467</a>, 9780199252466<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Pnkxofhi4mQC&amp;pg=PA596&amp;lpg=PA596&amp;dq=Massacre+of+the+Latins&amp;source=web&amp;ots=KZ5JtcG2jN&amp;sig=SJx8NwIiehNFz7OCT2ZIMSby1f8&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=RzGeSby8ONSujAetx6nLCw&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;resnum=10&amp;ct=result" class="external free" title="http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Pnkxofhi4mQC&amp;pg=PA596&amp;lpg=PA596&amp;dq=Massacre+of+the+Latins&amp;source=web&amp;ots=KZ5JtcG2jN&amp;sig=SJx8NwIiehNFz7OCT2ZIMSby1f8&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=RzGeSby8ONSujAetx6nLCw&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;resnum=10&amp;ct=result" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Pnkxofhi4mQC&amp;pg=PA596&amp;lpg=PA596&amp;dq=Massacre+of+the+Latins&amp;source=web&amp;ots=KZ5JtcG2jN&amp;sig=SJx8NwIiehNFz7OCT2ZIMSby1f8&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=RzGeSby8ONSujAetx6nLCw&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;resnum=10&amp;ct=result</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Oxford+Handbook+of+Byzantine+Studies&amp;rft.aulast=Gallagher&amp;rft.aufirst=Clarence&amp;rft.au=Gallagher%2C+Clarence&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3Bp.596&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0199252467%2C+9780199252466&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.co.uk%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DPnkxofhi4mQC%26pg%3DPA596%26lpg%3DPA596%26dq%3DMassacre%2Bof%2Bthe%2BLatins%26source%3Dweb%26ots%3DKZ5JtcG2jN%26sig%3DSJx8NwIiehNFz7OCT2ZIMSby1f8%26hl%3Den%26ei%3DRzGeSby8ONSujAetx6nLCw%26sa%3DX%26oi%3Dbook_result%26resnum%3D10%26ct%3Dresult&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:East-West_Schism"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Christiansen-23">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Christiansen_23-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Christiansen_23-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFChristiansen1997">Christiansen, Erik (1997). <i>The Northern Crusades</i>. London: Penguin Books. pp.&#160;287. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0140266534" class="internal">ISBN 0-14-026653-4</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Northern+Crusades&amp;rft.aulast=Christiansen&amp;rft.aufirst=Erik&amp;rft.au=Christiansen%2C+Erik&amp;rft.date=1997&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B287&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=Penguin+Books&amp;rft.isbn=0-14-026653-4&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:East-West_Schism"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
